# Camera Configuration — User Guide

## Overview

The **Camera Config** button opens a dialog that controls how the camera captures images. Settings are organised into four tabs. You do not need to change anything to run a normal experiment — the defaults are tuned for the 940 nm IR filter and the ~13 cm plate-to-lens distance. Use this dialog when you want to fine-tune image quality or troubleshoot focus.

---

## How to open it

1. Make sure **Live View is ON** (green "Turn Live View Off" button). The Focus tab's "Read from Camera" button only works while the camera is running.
2. Press **Camera Config**. The dialog opens without interrupting the live preview.
3. When you are done, press **Apply** to save your changes, then **Close**.

> **Tip:** After pressing Apply, watch the live preview on the right side of the screen. Changes take effect immediately so you can judge the result before closing the dialog.

---

## The four tabs

### General

Controls that apply globally to every capture regardless of illumination mode.

| Setting | What it does | When to change it |
|---|---|---|
| **Auto Exposure (AE)** | When checked, the camera automatically picks exposure time and gain. | Leave checked for general use. The IR-mode tabs override this for actual captures. |
| **Exposure Time** | How long the sensor collects light (µs). Only active when AE is off. | Grayed out while AE is on. |
| **Analogue Gain** | Electronic amplification of the sensor signal. Higher = brighter but noisier. | Grayed out while AE is on. |
| **AWB** | Auto White Balance. For IR imaging this should be **off** (the IR tabs enforce this automatically). | Leave unchecked. |
| **Contrast / Brightness / Saturation / Sharpness** | Image tone controls. | The IR tabs set these per mode; changing them here affects only the live preview's baseline. |
| **Noise Reduction Mode** | 0 = off, 1 = fast, 2 = high quality. | Leave at 0 for time-lapse (speed matters more than NR). |
| **HDR** | Combines multiple exposures. Only works on 3 MP mode. | Leave unchecked for standard use. |

---

### Focus

Controls whether the camera uses manual or automatic focus. **Manual focus is required** whenever the 940 nm bandpass filter is installed, because the camera's phase-detect autofocus (PDAF) does not work through that filter.

**Step-by-step: setting manual focus**

1. Check **"Use manual focus"**.
2. The **Lens Position** spinbox becomes active. The value is in *diopters* (1 ÷ distance in metres). A plate at 13 cm from the lens = 7.589 diopters, which is the preset default.
3. If you want to confirm or refine the value:
   - Make sure Live View is on.
   - Press **"Read Current Position from Camera"**.
   - The status line below the button will show the captured value in green (e.g. *"Captured: 7.589 D (≈ 13 cm)"*).
   - Adjust the spinbox if needed.
4. Press **Apply**.

> **Reference values**
> - 0.0 D = infinity (far away)
> - 4.0 D ≈ 25 cm
> - 7.589 D ≈ 13 cm ← default for this system
> - 10.0 D ≈ 10 cm

**What the focus label on the main screen means**

Below the Camera Config button you will see a small label:

- **Yellow text "MF: 7.589 D (13 cm)"** — manual focus is active at that position. This is what you want during normal experiments.
- **Grey text "Focus: Auto"** — the camera is using autofocus. Images may be blurry when the 940 nm filter is installed.

