### Front IR  *(Reflectance imaging)*

These settings are applied automatically whenever the illumination mode is set to **Front IR** or **Combined IR** — i.e. when the front LED panel is on and light bounces off the plate surface toward the camera.

| Setting | Default | Purpose |
|---|---|---|
| **AE** | On | Let the camera choose exposure for each plate. Suitable for reflectance where brightness varies plate-to-plate. |
| **Exposure** | 20 000 µs | Used only when AE is off. |
| **Contrast** | 1.10 | Slight boost to separate seedling from agar background. |
| **Sharpness** | 1.15 | Mild sharpening for leaf edges. |
| **Brightness** | 0.00 | No offset needed for reflectance. |

**When to adjust:** If reflectance images look consistently over- or under-exposed, try turning AE off and reducing or increasing Exposure. If seedlings look washed out against bright agar, lower Brightness slightly.

---

### Rear IR  *(Transmission imaging)*

These settings are applied automatically whenever the illumination mode is set to **Rear IR** or **Combined IR** when the rear panel is active — i.e. when light passes through the agar and the seedling casts a silhouette toward the camera.

| Setting | Default | Purpose |
|---|---|---|
| **AE** | **Off** | Fixed exposure prevents the camera from chasing brightness as seedlings grow and block more light over days. |
| **Exposure** | 9 000 µs | Tuned to keep the bright agar background below saturation. |
| **Gain** | 1.0 | Minimum gain to keep noise low in the brighter transmission image. |
| **Contrast** | 1.50 | Stronger boost to separate dark seedling silhouette from bright agar. |
| **Sharpness** | 1.40 | Higher sharpening to define thin hypocotyl and root edges. |
| **Brightness** | −0.05 | Small negative offset to prevent agar background from clipping to pure white. |

**When to adjust:** If the agar background looks pure white with no texture (overexposed), reduce Exposure by 1 000–2 000 µs. If seedlings are hard to see (underexposed), increase Exposure. Do not increase Gain above 2.0 — it adds noise that interferes with downstream image analysis.

> **Important:** Keep AE **off** for transmission. If you turn it on, the camera will gradually increase exposure as more seedlings fill the plate, making images from day 1 and day 5 incomparable.

