## How to know which settings are currently active

The **Illum** button on the main screen (the large coloured button below "Turn Live View On/Off") tells you which illumination mode — and therefore which set of camera settings — is currently in use:

| Button colour | Mode | Camera settings used |
|---|---|---|
| **Red — "Illum: Front IR"** | Front LED on only | Front IR tab values |
| **Blue — "Illum: Rear IR"** | Rear LED on only | Rear IR tab values |
| **Purple — "Illum: Combined IR"** | Both LEDs on | Rear IR tab values (transmission profile) |

The status bar at the top of the preview also confirms the active mode each time Live View starts, for example: *"Live View started. Front IR LED(s) ON."*

During an experiment, the mode is set when you press **Experiment Setup** and choose an illumination option. The correct preset is applied automatically before each plate is captured — you do not need to do anything manually.

---

## Quick-reference checklist before running an experiment

- [ ] Focus tab: **"Use manual focus"** is checked and Lens Position reads **7.589 D** (or your calibrated value).
- [ ] The focus label on the main screen shows yellow **MF: 7.589 D**.
- [ ] Front IR tab: AE is **on** (unless you have a reason to pin exposure for reflectance).
- [ ] Rear IR tab: AE is **off**; Exposure is set to a value that keeps agar background below saturation in your test image.
- [ ] Press **Apply**, then **Close**.
